nd","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Burnley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Burnley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Foljambe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>fol</i> ‘foolish, silly’ +  <i>jambe</i> ‘leg’, probably a nickname for a lame person, someone with a maimed or crooked leg;  compare  Belgian  . In Old French  <i>fol</i> could be used of something useless or of little value, e.g.  <i>farine folle</i> ‘mill dust’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulljames","meanings":["English: variant of   Foljambe   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Belgian","meanings":["Norman, English, Scottish: nickname from Anglo-Norman French  <i>bele jambe</i> ‘fine leg’."]}]},{"name":"Grace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the abstract noun (via Old French, from Latin <i>gratia</i>), this name occurs occasionally in the 15th century, and by the 1540s was among the most popular girls' names in some parishes. It has always been particularly popular in Scotland and northern England (borne, for example, by  Grace Darling , the lighthouse keeper's daughter whose heroism in  1838 , saving sailors in a storm, caught the popular imagination). In more recent times it was famous as the name of the actress  Grace Kelly  (  1928–82 ), who became  Princess Grace  of Monaco. In Ireland it is used as an Anglicized form of   Gráinne   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Grace Foljambe was born in 1500, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Henry Foljambe. She had at least 1 son and 4 daughters with Sir Richard Towneley."},"et":{"1500–":"1500–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1500–1555":"1500–1555","1490–1529":"1490–1529","1502–1608":"1502–1608","1502–Female":"1502–Surnud","1505–1543"